paragraph.content: Carbohydrate Counting for Diabetes Mellitus, Adult

text.paragraph:
Carbohydrate Counting for Diabetes Mellitus, Adult
Carbohydrate counting is a method of keeping track of how many carbohydrates you eat. Eating carbohydrates increases the amount of sugar (glucose) in the blood. Counting how many carbohydrates you eat improves how well you manage your blood glucose. This, in turn, helps you manage your diabetes.
Carbohydrates are measured in grams (g) per serving. It is important to know how many carbohydrates (in grams or by serving size) you can have in each meal. This is different for every person. A dietitian can help you make a meal plan and calculate how many carbohydrates you should have at each meal and snack.
What foods contain carbohydrates?
Carbohydrates are found in the following foods:
• Grains, such as breads and cereals.
• Dried beans and soy products.
• Starchy vegetables, such as potatoes, peas, and corn.
• Fruit and fruit juices.
• Milk and yogurt.
• Sweets and snack foods, such as cake, cookies, candy, chips, and soft drinks.
How do I count carbohydrates in foods?
There are two ways to count carbohydrates in food. You can read food labels or learn standard serving sizes of foods. You can use either of these methods or a combination of both.
Using the Nutrition Facts label
The Nutrition Facts list is included on the labels of almost all packaged foods and beverages in the United States. It includes:
• The serving size.
• Information about nutrients in each serving, including the grams of carbohydrate per serving.
To use the Nutrition Facts, decide how many servings you will have. Then, multiply the number of servings by the number of carbohydrates per serving. The resulting number is the total grams of carbohydrates that you will be having.
Learning the standard serving sizes of foods
When you eat carbohydrate foods that are not packaged or do not include Nutrition Facts on the label, you need to measure the servings in order to count the grams of carbohydrates.
• Measure the foods that you will eat with a food scale or measuring cup, if needed.
• Decide how many standard-size servings you will eat.
• Multiply the number of servings by 15. For foods that contain carbohydrates, one serving equals 15 g of carbohydrates.
◦ For example, if you eat 2 cups or 10 oz (300 g) of strawberries, you will have eaten 2 servings and 30 g of carbohydrates (2 servings x 15 g = 30 g).
• For foods that have more than one food mixed, such as soups and casseroles, you must count the carbohydrates in each food that is included.
The following list contains standard serving sizes of common carbohydrate-rich foods. Each of these servings has about 15 g of carbohydrates:
• 1 slice of bread.
• 1 six-inch (15 cm) tortilla.
• ⅓ cup or 2 oz (53 g) cooked rice or pasta.
• ½ cup or 3 oz (85 g) cooked or canned, drained and rinsed beans or lentils.
• ½ cup or 3 oz (85 g) starchy vegetable, such as peas, corn, or squash.
• ½ cup or 4 oz (120 g) hot cereal.
• ½ cup or 3 oz (85 g) boiled or mashed potatoes, or ¼ or 3 oz (85 g) of a large baked potato.
• ½ cup or 4 fl oz (118 mL) fruit juice.
• 1 cup or 8 fl oz (237 mL) milk.
• 1 small or 4 oz (106 g) apple.
• ½ or 2 oz (63 g) of a medium banana.
• 1 cup or 5 oz (150 g) strawberries.
• 3 cups or 1 oz (28.3 g) popped popcorn.
What is an example of carbohydrate counting?
To calculate the grams of carbohydrates in this sample meal, follow the steps shown below.
Sample meal
• 3 oz (85 g) chicken breast.
• ⅔ cup or 4 oz (106 g) brown rice.
• ½ cup or 3 oz (85 g) corn.
• 1 cup or 8 fl oz (237 mL) milk.
• 1 cup or 5 oz (150 g) strawberries with sugar-free whipped topping.
Carbohydrate calculation
1. Identify the foods that contain carbohydrates:
• Rice.
• Corn.
• Milk.
• Strawberries.
2. Calculate how many servings you have of each food:
• 2 servings rice.
• 1 serving corn.
• 1 serving milk.
• 1 serving strawberries.
3. Multiply each number of servings by 15 g:
• 2 servings rice x 15 g = 30 g.
• 1 serving corn x 15 g = 15 g.
• 1 serving milk x 15 g = 15 g.
• 1 serving strawberries x 15 g = 15 g.
4. Add together all of the amounts to find the total grams of carbohydrates eaten:
• 30 g + 15 g + 15 g + 15 g = 75 g of carbohydrates total.
What are tips for following this plan?
Shopping
• Develop a meal plan and then make a shopping list.
• Buy fresh and frozen vegetables, fresh and frozen fruit, dairy, eggs, beans, lentils, and whole grains.
• Look at food labels. Choose foods that have more fiber and less sugar.
• Avoid processed foods and foods with added sugars.
Meal planning
• Aim to have the same number of grams of carbohydrates at each meal and for each snack time.
• Plan to have regular, balanced meals and snacks.
Where to find more information
• American Diabetes Association: diabetes.org
• Centers for Disease Control and Prevention: cdc.gov
• Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics: eatright.org
• Association of Diabetes Care & Education Specialists: diabeteseducator.org
Summary
• Carbohydrate counting is a method of keeping track of how many carbohydrates you eat.
• Eating carbohydrates increases the amount of sugar (glucose) in your blood.
• Counting how many carbohydrates you eat improves how well you manage your blood glucose. This helps you manage your diabetes.
• A dietitian can help you make a meal plan and calculate how many carbohydrates you should have at each meal and snack.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
